03709nam a22006735i 9780691186467DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911864677 a10.1515/97806911864672doi  a(DE-B1597)501657  a(OCoLC)1076409472  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPQ6352b.Q57 2003eb 7aLIT0042802bisacsh04a863/.32221 aQuint, David, eauthor.10aCervantes's Novel of Modern Times :bA New Reading of Don Quijote /cDavid Quint. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2003  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tDON QUIJOTE, PART ONE -- tONE. Cervantes's Method and Meaning -- tTWO. "Dulcinea" -- tTHREE. "Princess Micomicona" -- tDON QUIJOTE, PART TWO -- tFOUR. The Gentler, Wiser Don Quijote -- tFIVE. Aristocrats -- tNOTES -- tINDEX  aThis book offers a radically new reading of Don Quijote, understanding it as a whole much greater than the sum of its famous parts. David Quint discovers a unified narrative and deliberate thematic design in a novel long taught as the very definition of the picaresque and as a rambling succession of individual episodes. Quint shows how repeated motifs and verbal details link the episodes, often in surprising and heretofore unnoticed ways. Don Quijote emerges as a work that charts and reflects upon the historical transition from feudalism to the modern times of a moneyed, commercial society. In Part One of the novel, this change is measured in a shift in the nature of erotic desire, and we find Don Quijote torn between his love for Dulcinea and his hopes to wed for wealth and social advancement. In Part Two, Don Quijote himself changes from anarchic madman to a gentler, wiser hero--a member of a middle class in the making. Throughout, Cervantes meditates on the literary form that he is inventing as a response to modernity, questioning the novel's relationship to other genres and the place of heroism and imagination within stories of everyday life. A new and coherent guide through the maze-like structure of Don Quijote, this book invites readers to appreciate the perennial modernity of Cervantes's masterpiece---a novel that confronts times not so distant from our own.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691186467zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691186467.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN